  "siteName": "The Ancient Gaming Noob",
  "favicon": "",
  "text": "The dragon has been slain… twice… which was the essence of the last post about Enshrouded.  And so the question becomes… what next? Welcome to Enshrouded Since Enshrouded is in early access, it has not delivered all the content that has been planned yet.  There was even a roadmap about that a bit back. The 2025 Roadmap So there is more to come.  But, at the moment, we are at the level cap of 35, we are at flame level 8, and have defeated what is currently the final boss.  What do we do now? For starters, there are still quests.  My journal page has a list more than 20 quests I could dig into. Keeping track of things The quest thing is a bit divided.  There are all the individual quests that are complete only when you do them.  Then there are the server quests that are complete when one person on the server does them.  But you can still do some of those server quests.  I don’t think you can find any of the missing souls a second time. The jumping puzzle to get to this one was a chore But some of the other ones… maybe?  I have only lit 4 of the 8 balefires needed to summon the dragon that we fought last time around.  I assume that I could go click on the other 4 and get credit.  But those don’t all grant something beyond xp, so maybe I should hold off on those Well, there is always exploration.  The hand crafted map in Enshrouded is excellent for exploration.  To start with, there is stuff squirreled away all over the map.  I keep an axe in my primary tool bar because there is often a suspicious bookcase covering a secret passage or hidden alcove, or maybe a flimsy wooden barrier behind which you might spy the gleam of a hidden chest. There isn’t a hidden bounty in every room you will visit, but it is there in enough rooms than you may feel the need to check them all… and break apart every bookcase to be sure. Likewise, there isn’t a chest buried in every pile of rubble… and sometimes it is pretty obvious when there is one there. A pile of rubble with a banner in it is a give away And sometimes it is that pile of rubble in a dark niche in the back of a cave that has a chest. Found it Then there is the rubble that hides passages to other locations.  If it is a place they really want you to go there can be an explosive barrel or two placed to suggest that maybe you should blow this particular bit of rubble sky high. Go after all the rubble! Exploration also gets you to the various bits of lore seeded throughout the game world.  The journal also has a lore section that will tell you what you have seen and what is still out there to find. Tracking the various lore pieces Those also give you a bit of xp when you find them… but mostly tell you the story of the world and what happened.  For me it is like so much quest text, even when I read it I still forget it almost immediately, but somebody out there probably loves that. The world itself is also pretty and interesting and has a variety of scenery that is worth seeking out, if that is your thing. Our group out crossing an ice lake Above the ice lake is a large frozen waterfall… which, to my chagrin, does not have a cave behind it.  At least not that I have found so far.  But I got out my pick axe to try. The most rewarding… at least in terms of character progression… things to find are the various shroud roots hidden throughout the land.  Chopping those down shroud roots earns you skill points.  That was what we were out doing last weekend, chasing down some of the remaining ones we had previously missed. A shroud root always looks dramatic Some are hidden deep underground, others are barely hidden at all.  A few are just sitting there, in the shroud, visible if you happen to walk by. The achievements indicate that I have found all of the shroud roots available.  There are a couple of well hidden ones I spent some time reaching.  We’ll have to have another expedition to get everybody there.  And then we’re kind of done with progress. I still have a few achievements I could wrap up according to Steam. My remaining achievements Finding all the flame shrines and sanctums requires some diligent exploration.  We’ll see if I have it in me. Otherwise we are down to base building… though base building is a huge feature of the game, so don’t let me undersell that even if it isn’t really my thing, farming some chests for the occasional weapon or ring upgrade, and looking for the remaining pieces for that mosaic we picked up. The bard tugging at my sleeve while I admire our progress So there are things to do.  But I also feel a bit of a lull in activity as well.  I don’t want to give it up entirely, not yet, while there is still some exploration to be done, however it also isn’t scratching that all important (to the point of obsession at times) character progression itch. Which is not to say anything negative about the game.  It has kept us occupied for four months at this point.  It is high on the list of reasons we have not been in Cataclysm.  I recommend it and want to see it completed. I still have a few more posts about Enshrouded to go, but the state of play now that we’re reach the level cap and slain the dragon is more of filling in the gaps than seeking new adventures.",
